  "doi": "10.1002/eji.201948085",
  "title": "TCR-induced alteration of primary MHC peptide anchor residue.",
  "journal": "European journal of immunology",
  "year": 2019,
  "authors": "Madura F, Rizkallah PJ, Legut M, Holland CJ, Fuller A, Bulek A, Schauenburg AJ, Trimby A, Hopkins JR, Wells SA, Godkin A, Miles JJ, Sami M, Li Y, Liddy N, Jakobsen BK, Loveridge EJ, Cole DK, Sewell AK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "The MEL5 T-cell receptor recognizes the nonapeptide AAGIGILTV (derived from the MART-1 melanoma tumor antigen) presented by HLA-A*02:01, a clinically relevant epitope that exists in both nona- and decapeptide forms at the tumor cell surface. Crystal or cryo-EM structural analysis revealed that TCR binding induces an altered conformation of the peptide's anchor residues at the MHC interface\u2014a \"flexing\" mechanism that deviates from the canonical peptide-MHC binding mode. This induced-fit mechanism explains why the dominant nonapeptide form at melanoma surfaces is poorly recognized by most clinical TCRs despite being the naturally presented species, accounting for the disappointing clinical results of prior MART-1-targeted immunotherapies. The finding demonstrates that molecular plasticity of the peptide-MHC complex is a key determinant of TCR recognition and has direct implications for optimizing T-cell engineering and cancer immunotherapy design.",
 "noncanonical": {
